n james smith was born around  in westminster england   john begins his career with the hudson’s bay company    in  john signed a contract with the hudson’s bay company hbc the  year old sailed to albany factory on the prince of wales to begin his career as an assistant writer and labourer there     in  the hbc divided rupert’s land into two new jurisdictions the northern and southern departments thomas thomas  was appointed superintendant of the southern department fort albany moose factory and eastmain factorywilliam auld  was appointed superintendant of the northern department churchill york factory winnipeg and saskatchewan districts   from  to  john spent most of his time as a labourer at trading posts inland from albany along the albany river mainly at marten falls gloucester house and henley house    john and an indian woman named mary    during this period john was “country wed” to an indian woman simply named mary around  their first child richard was born   in  john was placed in charge at marten falls in  he was assistant at lower henley house and in  he was placed in charge of the post at attawapiskat north of albany near the mouth of the attawapiskat river in  his second son john was born there   union of the hudson’s bay company and the north west company    in  union of the north west company nwc and the hudson’s bay company hbc occurred ending years of bitter rivalry for dominance of the fur trade in western canada after the merger almost  employees lost their jobs since the single hbc organization that emerged had no need for most of their voyageurs and retired fur traders   in  john was discharged from service and became a “free hunter” in the albany district   at the time of the hbcnwc union sir george simpson  became the governor of rupert’s land on may   simpson reported to the board of governors of the hbc that he had established a fort at the junction of the red and assiniboine rivers he named it fort garry the upper fort around this fort was to grow the city of winnipeg   john james settles in little britain red river    by  jj retired to red river and settled in the lockport – little britain area   on july   john was churchwed at st john’s to his country wife mary by this time they had two more children william  harriet   the red river census of  indicated that john had a house and a canoe and that he had two acres of land under cultivation the family consisted of three sons under the age of  richard john and william and a daughter under  harriet in  daughter mary was born   in  construction of lower fort garry was begun on the hbc reserve land right next to john’s property john’s wife mary died that year   marriage to nancy favel    on apr   john james smith remarried to nancy favel daughter of jennyjane pawpitch and humphrey martin favel  jenny jane was only about  years old jj was then about  years old   in  parish map shows john james smith as the owner of lot  just to the south of the lower ft garry hbc reserve land   part of henry hind’s map based on his observations of    in pieces of the past pg  frank walters born  speaks of a james smith  he says many of the settlers heated limestone to make their own lime wash whitewash but others made a business of it  one of the first to construct a kiln was james smith who built his kiln near where the st andrews locks are now and sold lime to his neighbours   in  son henry was born john’s first child with nancy   in  son richard married nancy ann robertson daughter of clementine harper  john robertson    in  daughter harriet became the nd wife of james anderson son of mary  james anderson sr   more about james anderson sr   st peters indian settlement   it appears that john  nancy moved at some point to the st peters indian settlement where son james was born in  he was baptized there on aug   by reverend john smithurst and was actually later referred to as an ‘indian’   by  nancy had given birth to two more children thomas and ann elizabeth   in  son john jr married mary taylor daughter of jane prince  surveyor george taylor  more about george taylor   john’s last child was samuel born in    around  son william married charlotte mowat daughter of margaret indian and edward mowat   more about edward mowat   on oct   john james simth died buried at st andrews   around  daughter mary married roderick saunders son of margaret cook  william sanderson aka saunders   more about william sanderson aka saunders   in  daughter catherine married her brotherinlaw david mowat   around  son james married nancy smith of so far unknown origins james was among the first settlers near clandeboye medicine creek around  daughter ann elizabeth married john sanderson son of elizabeth anderson  james sanderson   more about james sanderson   canadian confederation manitoba becomes a province    on july   the british colonies in north america were united under the british north american act to become the dominion of canada  sir john a macdonald  was appointed as canada’s first prime minister a month later he won the first federal electionwilliam mcdougall  became the minister of public works and he begannegotiations to acquire rupert’s land from the hbc   on feb   son samuel married mary ann desmarais at st mary’s anglican church in portage la prairie daughter of sophia erasmus  jean baptiste desmarais   more about jean baptiste desmarais   around  son thomas was at fort vermillion on the peace river in northern alberta where he married madeleine lizotte daughter of sophie tourangeau and michel lizotte  from quebec   more about michel lizotte   around  son henry married mary nee stevens lyons daughter of mary meenish  richard stevens    on july  manitoba became the fifth province of canada the canadian government having acquired the territory previously governed by the hbc   widow nancy smith would spend the rest of her life with the family of her son thomas in st andrews where she died on aug     please post comments  queries at this link